    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical Note</head>
      <p>Seamus Deane (<date normal="1940" type="schema:birthDate">1940</date>-), Irish poet and educator, was born in <geogname
          authfilenumber="2643735" source="geonames" role="schema:birthPlace">Derry, Northern Ireland</geogname>. He attended
          <corpname authfilenumber="Queen%27s_University_Belfast" source="dbpedia" role="schema:alumniOf">Queen's
          University, Belfast</corpname> and <corpname authfilenumber="University_of_Cambridge"
          source="dbpedia" role="schema:alumniOf">Cambridge University</corpname>. He was a professor of English and
        American Literature at <corpname authfilenumber="University_College_Dublin" source="dbpedia"
           role="schema:worksFor">University College, Dublin</corpname> and a professor of Irish Studies at the <corpname
          authfilenumber="University_of_notre_dame" source="dbpedia" role="schema:worksFor">University of Notre
          Dame</corpname>. He was also a founding director of the <corpname
          authfilenumber="Field_Day_Theatre_Company" source="dbpedia" role="schema:founderOf">Field Day Theatre
          Company</corpname>, along with <persname authfilenumber="38545317" source="viaf" role="schema:colleague">David
          Hammond</persname>, <persname authfilenumber="109557338" source="viaf" role="schema:colleague">Seamus
          Heaney</persname>, and <persname authfilenumber="108291535" source="viaf" role="schema:colleague">Tom
          Paulin</persname>. Deane has published several works of poetry and non-fiction, as well as
        one novel. His collections of poetry include Gradual Wars, Rumors and History Lessons; his
        non-fiction includes Heroic Styles: The Tradition of an Idea, Celtic Revivals: Essays in
        Modern Irish Literature, A Short History of Irish Literature, Strange Country, and French
        Revolution and Enlightenment in England, 1789-1832. His novel, Reading in the Dark, was
        nominated for a Booker Prize in 1996.</p>

    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
      <p>The collection consists of the papers of Irish poet and educator Seamus Deane. It contains
        writings by Deane and others, correspondence, journals and business records. Writings by
        others include works by <persname authfilenumber="76315726" source="viaf">Brian
          Friel</persname> and <persname authfilenumber="91961511" source="viaf">Thomas
          Kilroy</persname>. The collection also contains materials relating to <persname
          authfilenumber="109557338" source="viaf">Seamus Heaney</persname>'s work, particularly a
        draft of his 1975 poetry collection North. Significant correspondents include <persname
          authfilenumber="109176234" source="viaf">Denis Donoghue</persname>, Seamus Heaney
        (restricted), <persname authfilenumber="34500781" source="viaf">Thomas Kinsella</persname>,
          <persname authfilenumber="39398205" source="viaf">Michael</persname> and Evelyn Longley,
          <persname authfilenumber="120096893" source="viaf">Medbh McGuckian</persname>, <persname
          authfilenumber="110228045" source="viaf">Derek Mahon</persname>, and <persname
          authfilenumber="108291535" source="viaf">Tom Paulin</persname>.</p>
    </scopecontent>
